name: WSJ
text: The #Emmys are virtual this year. “A train wreck? Could be. Hope not. But if I was a viewer I’d tune in for that,” says the executive producer of the ceremony. Here's how it's all coming together. https://t.co/R9WWVWFaeT

name: WSJ
text: As the #Emmys get underway, HBO’s limited series “Watchmen” leads the contenders with 26 nominations. Other top nominees include Amazon’s “The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel,” Netflix’s “Ozark” and HBO’s “Succession.” https://t.co/7aS8yh335C

name: WSJ
text: Taking home the second award of the night and the second for "Schitt's Creek," Eugene Levy wins Outstanding Lead Actor In A Comedy Series for his role as Johnny Rose. Here is a list of tonight's nominees and winners. #Emmys  https://t.co/iw4GnExHtM

name: WSJ
text: Daniel Levy wins the third award for "Schitt's Creek" with Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series. He spoke to @WSJMag about the show’s final season and 15 nominations, "It is truly a fairy-tale ending for us." https://t.co/iUdYU6VSmo

name: WSJ
text: "Schitt's Creek" is on a roll! The Canadian comedy takes home the fourth and fifth awards of the night with wins in Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series and for Daniel Levy in Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series. #Emmys https://t.co/qkEK8e5ZLd

name: WSJ
text: "Schitt's Creek" wins Outstanding Comedy Series and Annie Murphy wins Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series for her role as Alexis Rose. Our winners from the #Emmys so far: https://t.co/iw4GnExHtM

name: WSJ
text: Emmy-nominated writers and directors spent their year staring at a television, just like the rest of us. We spoke to four nominees about the movies and shows that they couldn’t stop watching—new, nominated and otherwise. https://t.co/RkXWI0W0GF

name: WSJ
text: Mark Ruffalo wins Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie for playing divergent identical twins in the adaptation of “I Know This Much Is True” #Emmys https://t.co/4zaD3CRHka
